The attached spreadsheet contains the various constraints in mathematical notation, and is much easier to follow; however, I will also try to spell them out in words here. Please note that some of these checks cannot be applied until after the appendix D calculations have been run.
The product of the Tax multiplier and the sum of the expense ratio and expected loss ratio must be less than or equal to 1.

The minimum premium factor must be greater than or equal to the tax multiplier multiplied by the sum of the basic premium factor and excess loss factor (the excess loss factor is the policy excess ratio multiplied by the expected loss ratio -- see line 5 of appendix D calculations).
The minimum premium factor must be less than the tax multiplier multiplied by the sum of the expense ratio and the expected loss ratio.
The maximum premium factor must be greater than the tax multiplier multiplied by the sum of the expense ratio and the expected loss ratio.
The max premium factor must be less than or equal to the min premium factor plus the product of 10, the loss conversion factor, the expected limited loss ratio, and the tax multiplier.
Loss Conversion factor must be greater than or equal to 1.0
Tax multiplier must be greater than or equal to 1.0
The basic premium factor must be greater than or equal to zero.

The difference between the entry ratios corresponding to the aggregate excess loss factor (AELF) and aggregate minimum loss factor (AMLF) must be equal to the difference between the maximum and minimum premium factor, divided by the product of the loss conversion factor, expected limited loss ratio, and the tax multiplier (see attached for formula).

The difference between the aggregate excess loss factors corresponding to the entry ratios for the AMLF and AELF must equal the sum of the expense ratio and expected loss ratio, less the min premium factor divided by the tax multiplier, divided by the product of the loss conversion factor and the expected limited loss ratio (see attached for formula).
The Expense Ratio must be greater than the negative of the expected loss ratio.
